shared_text:
Holton Middle School
September 10 at 8:04 PM ·

Parents... we have had several kids coming to school this week at HMS without a mask.

We were lucky that the school was able to offer every student 5 white cotton masks at the beginning of the year. We were even able to keep some masks back as extras to help out students when they do forget...however, eventually, even our back up supply will run out.

In today's world, we all know that face masks are important and a requirement for school. Please make sure that your students come to school everyday with a mask.

Thank you for all that you and your students are doing to help support a safe and healthy environment at Holton Middle School.

post_text: Holton Special Education Cooperative has a Paraprofessional position for the 2020-2021 school year at Holton Elementary School. This is a Fulltime position with 32.5 hours per week. $12.85 to start with a differential increase for levels of education and years of qualified experience. Please contact Jeff Price at j.price@holtonks.net 785-364-2990, for additional information and an explanation of fringe benefits. You may fill out an online application at www.holtonks.net - select Careers tab from top menu, then select classified application from bottom menu. Indicate Paraprofessional in the “Position Applied for” section and then write Holton Elementary School in the “other” line at the bottom of the section. Screening of applications will begin immediately, and continue until the position is filled.

FREE MEALS STARTING TUESDAY

Starting Tuesday, September 8, Holton will be offering FREE breakfast and FREE lunch for all students enrolled in our school district – In-person or remote. The USDA has decided to offer free meals and hopefully this will continue through this semester. It is not retroactive so meal bought and paid up until this date will be deducted from your child’s food service account. Any existing or prepaid money in your child’s food service account can remain in their account until next semester.

Good morning parents and staff,

The high school will be changing its status today and will be starting school in full remote mode starting at noon today in 3rd block and from there, classes will run through 4th block. There will not be 1st and 2nd hour classes.

Parents who would like for their high school student to have a lunch today, please contact the HS office at 364-2181 by 9:30 this morning and we can coordinate picking up a lunch at the elementary school from 10:00 to 10:45 on the west side of the school off Dakota Street.

Thank you for being patient with us as this will help our staff determine any difficulties as we proceed this school year.

post_text:
The Holton Board of Education has postponed the start of school with students until Monday, August 24 so that staff can prepare for the reopening of school with in-person students and students who choose remote learning. Also of interest on the calendar - on Friday, August 28 there will be No School so that staff can make adjustments to any issues the school may have early on.

The school district appreciates parents participation with the latest survey and this data, along with our summer school data on what worked and what did not, will help the staff develop a reopening plan that not only keeps our students and staff safe, but will help us meet the needs of our students academically. More information will be coming soon.

post_text:
Parents,

Please take the opportunity to enroll your students for this school year online from the safety of your home. Our goal is to reduce the number of parents that need to come on site for enrollment on Monday, August 3rd. If you have misplaced that initial email or it went to your spam or junk folder, you can look at our website to find out how to enroll your student at www.holtonks.net.

If you need assistance, you can send an email to enroll@holtonks.net. You can also call (785) 362-1451 to leave our tech staff a message. Either way, please be sure to include the following in your message:

• Your name,
• the name of your student,
• and a good call back number.

Our tech people plan to respond no later than the next business day.

Kansas State High School Activities Association
July 15 at 5:40 PM ·

The KSHSAA believes participation in school and school activities is critical for the students of Kansas and we strive to provide those opportunities for students this fall. This Friday (7/17) the KSHSAA had planned to distribute considerations and guidance for all fall activities to take place starting August 17. With the announcement today (7/15) from Governor Kelly, we will not release any information Friday. Rather we will go back and look at models and plans that are in place with a delayed start and release information when appropriate.

post_text:
Parents and Staff,

Our Food Service Director, Mike Adkins has done it again. The USDA Farmers to Families Food Box Program is going on again tomorrow, Thursday, July 2, from the back of Holton Elementary School. We will be ready to distribute food boxes by 8 a.m. We ask everyone to drive though our bus lane on Dakota heading north and turn onto 6th street toward the back of the school to help with congestion on 6th street. We are being told that this truck will have fruits, vegetables, and dairy. Some of the staff have again volunteered to distribute the food boxes so we know they will be working hard to get the products out efficiently.

This program is not based on need, any income requirements, or residency, yet we encourage people to come get boxes if they are struggling or want to pick up food for their shut-in neighbors and people in need who can not get out. This is open to everyone.

post_text:
The USDA Farmers to Families Food Box Program is going on again tomorrow, Thursday, June 18, and next Thursday, June 25, from the back of Holton Elementary School. Tomorrow and next week, the truck is to come earlier, so we think we will be ready to distribute food boxes by 8 a.m. We ask everyone to drive though our bus lane on Dakota heading north and turn onto 6th street toward the back of the school to help with congestion on 6th street. We are being told that this truck will have fruits, vegetables, and dairy. Some of the elementary staff have again volunteered to distribute the food boxes this time so we know they will be working extra hard to get the products out efficiently.

This program is not based on need, any income requirements, or residency, yet we encourage people to come get boxes if they are struggling or want to pick up food for their shut-in neighbors and people in need who can not get out. This is open to everyone.

Holton Public Schools USD 336
June 16 at 2:16 PM ·

On June 22nd, the Onaga Community HealthCare System and Holton Community Hospital Family Practice will be hosting a free physical day here at Holton High School, in the varsity gym. These physicals are free of cost for all incoming 7th- 12th grade students. The Kansas State High School Activities Association has put out a new physical form that can be picked up during the morning weights sessions, or printed off of the KSHSAA website. Please have the KSHSAA physical form filled out and signed in the appropriate areas before arriving on June 22nd.

Students will enter through the Southeast doors of the varsity gym, at the corner of 9th and New York. We have split the sessions into four time slots depending on your last name. The schedule is as follows.

Last names starting with:
A-D – 9:00am-10:30am
E-K – 10:30am-12:00pm
L-P – 1:00pm-2:30pm
R-Z – 2:30pm-4:00pm

post_text:
The USDA Farmers to Family food box program went by fast today as we ran out of food to distribute by 10:10 this morning. The semi-tractor trailer full of food included three different items to disperse to each family and the elementary staff who helped today were extremely organized and efficient. We are sorry not everyone in line received the food items.

We are looking to do this one more time, but it is based on many factors and we usually do not get much notice to determine if will receive the food boxes or not. Today marked three weeks in a row and we were able to participate and hand out food. The school could not have done this without Mike Adkins, the Holton Food Service Director, working hard to make this program available in our communities. We also have been lucky to obtain volunteers from our school (Staff and students) to help distribute over 900 to 1,100 boxes of food each week. 24 to 26 pallets of food have gone out each week. When we know more about next week, we will let the community know.

post_text: The board of education has authorized the staff to offer in-person summer school for students in elementary, middle school, and high school starting July 6 through July 24. Eligibility for elementary summer school and some middle school students will be based on indicators showing need. Some middle school students and high school students will also be invited for credit recovery. We plan to work out more details and send out letters soon so we can determine if those invited want to participate. More details about summer school will be in the letter but this will look a lot like summer school in the past as we will be doing this in the morning only.

Topeka VA Medical Center
May 13 at 2:22 PM ·

VA Eastern Kansas says.... THANK YOU to Natalie and Brooke! These amazing young ladies from USD 336 (Holton Public Schools) made these mask straps using a 3D printer and will be dropping the first batch of 100 this week for our healthcare workers. When asked why, these selfless superstars said: “We just wanted to help the healthcare workers while in this pandemic. Because if we can do something to help, this is where we can help.” Hat's off to these beautiful leaders of the next generation. When COVID-19 is behind us, we want to invite you both out to personally meet some of the staff who you have made such an impact with. Keep being great, Natalie & Brooke!!!

May 13 at 2:22 PM ·

VA Eastern Kansas says.... THANK YOU to Natalie and Brooke! These amazing young ladies from USD 336 (Holton Public Schools) made these mask straps using a 3D printer and will be dropping the first batch of 100 this week for our healthcare workers. When asked why, these selfless superstars said: “We just wanted to help the healthcare workers while in this pandemic. Because if we can do something to help, this is where we can help.” Hat's off to these beautiful leaders of the next generation. When COVID-19 is behind us, we want to invite you both out to personally meet some of the staff who you have made such an impact with. Keep being great, Natalie & Brooke!!!

shared_text:
GOVERNOR.KANSAS.GOV
Governor Kelly issues temporary, statewide Stay Home order in ongoing effort to combat COVID-19 - Governor of the State of Kansas

Governor Laura Kelly
March 28 at 12:22 PM ·

As part of ongoing efforts to limit the spread of COVID-19 in Kansas, today I issued Executive Order 20-16, making Kansas the 22nd state in the nation to institute a temporary, statewide stay-home order.

The order will exist in conjunction with the Kansas Essential Function Framework for COVID-19 response efforts and will take effect at 12:01 a.m. on Monday, March 30. The measure will be in place at least until Sunday, April 19.

Under the order, Kansans must remain at home unless going to work to perform an essential function; obtaining food, medicine or other household necessities; seeking medical care; caring for children, pets, family members or others; or exercising outside.

shared_text:
Kansas State Treasurer Jake LaTurner
March 24 at 3:31 PM ·

With high school students across the state home from school the Kansas State Treasurer’s Office has a great new tool we have launched to help parents and students find money to pay for educational opportunities after high school. Whether you have a student looking at tech school, vocational school, or a traditional college we are thrilled to announce that we have partnered with Sallie Mae to provide an exceptional way to access over 5-million scholarships worth over $24-billion quickly and easily on our new Kansas ScholarShop website.

https://www.kansasstatetreasurer.com/scholarshop.html

We tested this platform at Washburn Rural High School in February, before schools were suspended for COVID-19, and the students and teachers had great success searching. The website is now ready to be used by students statewide.

The tool is simple and can be customized very specifically to the student's interests. We encourage you to give it a try!

post_text:
Parents and Staff,

The Jackson County Health Department has decided at this time to cancel all three Jackson County School for this coming week, March 16 through March 20. Also, the Kansas State Department of Education in a conference call at 4 p.m. today is strongly recommending that all schools in the state be out of session for this coming week as well. I want to commend Angie Reith, The Jackson County Health Official for her leadership in these trying times. She has worked extremely hard the last few days keeping us informed of what is going on in our county and in our state. She is looking out for the safety of our children and our community and we are lucky she is helping with this crisis. 12-month staff will follow building closure guidelines for reporting for work and custodians will be using this week to do more extensive cleaning of our facilities. All other staff are to stay out of the buildings at this time but later you may be called upon if needed to plan for what we do next. Thank you and please stay safe.

Bob Davies
Holton Superintendent of Schools

post_text:
Parents and staff,

I will be issuing a statement regarding school being opened or closed on Monday by 6 o’clock tonight. All week I have been monitoring the COVID-19 virus situation from reputable sources like the CDC, the World Health Organization, and the Kansas Department of Health and Environment. This morning, the Jackson County Health Department asked all three superintendents in our area to attend a meeting with the experts in healthcare in our community to specifically discuss schools. Throughout the day today, there are several other meetings and webinars scheduled that will give us more insight into what to do moving forward. After all of these sessions today, we plan to discuss what is best for our community moving forward and I will issue a statement by 6 p.m.

Bob Davies
Holton Superintendent of School

post_text:
Parents and community members

Below is an invitation to a community presentation on the topic of student safety and social media being hosted in Jackson County at the Royal Valley Middle School in Mayetta on Wednesday, March 18, at 6 p.m. If your son or daughter has a cell phone or is on social media, you may not realize the potential harm, pressure, and liability that our students face constantly from their mobile device. Officer Calvert was the County School Resource officer but now he is working at the Kansas State Department of Education as their school safety specialist. His presentations are informative with a fun flair and he can help parents and adults understand the problems and pitfalls of this misunderstood topic as it concerns our youth in a constantly changing medium. Please consider attending as all Jackson County parents and adults are welcome!
